record.title: Greeks
record.detail: Sydney's Hellenic community is one of the city's largest and most influential, with a long and complex history. Greek-speaking people came from many parts of the Mediterranean, as well as Hellas itself, and have maintained their diverse cultural traditions at the same time as becoming part of Sydney's institutions and cultural and business life.

record.title: Wedding party, Ayia Sophia Church 1936
Private collection

record.detail: Permission from owner of photo, Zeny Giles: From: Zeny Giles [mailto:zenygiles@gmail.com] Sent: Fri 12/23/2011 7:14 PM To: Paul Howard Subject: Re: Photographic permission I would be happy for the photo taken of my parents' wedding at St Sophia Church, Dowling Street, Sydney, on 16th February, 1936, to be used by the Dictionary of Sydney. My father, Michael Doratis emigrated from Cyprus in 1927, my mother, Chrisaphina Papacotis came with her sister and brother in 1924. Sincerely, Zeny Doratis Giles.

record.title: The
record.detail: The wedding party stands on the steps of Ayia Sophia Greek Orthodox Church in Paddington on 16 February 1936, after the marriage of Nina Papacotis, whose family migrated from Castellorizo, and Michael Doratis, from Cyprus. The interwar period was a time of growth for the Greek community in Sydney.

record.title: Many
record.detail: The foundation stone of the Greek Orthodox Cathedral of St Sophia, on the corner of Napier and South Dowling streets, was laid in February 1927 by the Consul-General for Greece, Leonidas Chrysanthopoulos. Architect Walter Leslie modelled the building on Grecian architecture with Byzantine decorations inside.
